&gt; &gt; Two thoughts on Jerome and computer typing in quickscript:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I have only recently begun to read Shavian and Quickscript.  I enjoy
&gt;
&gt; &gt; some of the advantages of both.  Read&#39;s extension of abreviations
&gt; and
&gt; &gt; abreviated words in Quickscript seem wonderful.  However, I find the
&gt;
&gt; &gt; small &quot;curleys&quot; in the type version of Jerome hard on my eyes.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I really appreciate the hard work done on Jerome, but believe
&gt; &gt; Quickscript readers could also do with a font that does not look
&gt; like
&gt; &gt; penmanship.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;From reading Read&#39;s booklet on Quickscript, it appears that most of
&gt;
&gt; &gt; the half letter and joinings were instituted to make writing with a
&gt; &gt; pen easier, not reading easier.  Much like script penmanship, I
&gt; &gt; believe that most of them detract from the readability of the text
&gt; &gt; when the text is in an electronic version.  (BTW, I gave up on
&gt; script
&gt; &gt; writing in the seventh grade about 36 years ago and have been
&gt; &gt; printing ever since so that my handwriting can be easily read.  I
&gt; use
&gt; &gt; the computer to write letters for the same reason.)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I can not imagine wanting to read a font on the computer which
&gt; &gt; attempts to mimic script...  I know they exist, but to prefer this
&gt; &gt; for everyday reading!  No thanks.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I have been thinking along two lines.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; First, is there already a version of Quickscript True Type font
&gt; which
&gt; &gt; looks more like the Junior Quickscript of Read&#39;s manual?  If not, I
&gt; &gt; may invest a little time and come up with one.  I think it could
&gt; &gt; improve readability in the way that ghoti and lionspaw are very
&gt; &gt; readable Shavian scripts.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Second, is there a way to program the keyboard interface to scan for
&gt;
&gt; &gt; combination letters other than shift, ctl and alt?  I recently
&gt; worked
&gt; &gt; on a 7 key keyboard that used &quot;chord fingerings&quot;  for letters.
&gt; Chord
&gt; &gt; fingerings seem like a natural for phonetic languages like
&gt; &gt; Quickscript.  It is easy enough to remember cap T for &quot;theater&quot; but
&gt; &gt; cap Y for &quot;oil&quot;??  Would it not be nice to just press the o and i
&gt; &gt; keys?  The computer would run the following algorhythm when you
&gt; &gt; pressed the o key... hmmm... o key, must be an o, ... no the i key
&gt; is
&gt; &gt; also pressed must be an &quot;oil&quot;  now wait for the next letter press.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I have not worked the keyboard interface to see if this kind of
&gt; chord
&gt; &gt; keying could be instituted within the present operating systems or
&gt; &gt; not.  Any computer programmmers with feedback?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Rick
&gt; &gt;
